, and those deemed sexually deviant. The volume also presents a more geographically diverse Middle Ages by including sources from Central and Eastern Europe as well as the Mediterranean. Sources are organized in thematic chapters, covering everything from "Heresy and Inquisition" to "Disease and Disability." Each document is preceded by a brief introduction and followed by questions for discussion, making The Intolerant Middle Ages an excellent entrance into the lives and struggles of minorities in the medieval world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPersecutionzEuropexHistoryyMiddle Ages, 500-1500vSources. 0aPersecutionzEuropexHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500vSources. 0aTolerationzEuropexHistoryyMiddle Ages, 500-1500vSources. 0aTolerationzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500vSources. 0aViolencezEuropexHistoryyMiddle Ages, 500-1500vSources. 0aViolencezEuropexHistoryyTo 1500vSources. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aJews.  aMiddle Ages.  aMuslims.  adisabled.  adisplaced.  aheresy.  ahistory of disability.  ainquisition.  aintolerance.  amedieval Mediterranean.  amedieval minorities.  apersecution.  aprimary sources.  asexual deviance.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753333540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487533335423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487533335.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles